Notes: There is no explicit path in the ontology corresponding to an internal row identifier. This field is best treated as an internal technical identifier for tracking and not mapped to the ontology directly. If an identifier must be mapped, one could consider using an rdfs:label or a custom annotation property.

Column 'patient_id' represents a link to the patient entity related to the measurement. Path 1 directly associates Measurement with Patient. I considered 2-hop paths like Path 26 (hasPatient/hasPatientIdentifier) and Path 32 (hasPatient/hasIdentifier), but without a structured identifier or additional context, mapping to the Patient entity is most precise.

The 'measurement_code' is a code string (e.g., LOINC, ICD-10) identifying the type of measurement. The optimal path is 50 (hasCode/Code/hasIdentifier), which captures the code value itself. Alternatives considered: Path 4 (hasCode), but the 2-hop 'hasIdentifier' is more specific for the code string.

The 'measurement_value' is a numeric result. The best matching path is 86 (hasQuantity/Quantity/hasValue) with datatype double. Considered path 14 (hasQuantity), but the 2-hop path provides a direct mapping to the value.
The 'measurement_unit' specifies the unit for the value (e.g., mg/dL). Path 85 (hasQuantity/Quantity/hasUnit) maps directly to the Unit entity. No 1-hop path applies; this 2-hop path is optimal.

The 'measurement_date' records when the measurement was taken. Path 20 (hasMeasurementDateTime) is the most semantically specific. Considered path 18 (hasDateTime), but hasMeasurementDateTime is more precise for measurement events.
